## Importing with the Content Browser

(#Bookmark1)

The **Content Browser** is located in the lower-left corner of the Editor interface (pictured below).

![](ContentBrowser.jpg)

**Clicking** on the **Content Browser's** ![](ImportButton.jpg) button opens a file dialog, enabling you to add assets to your project.

## Importing using Click and Drag

(#Bookmark2)

**Dragging** files from your hard drive into the **Content Browser** (pictured below) is another way of adding content to your project.

![](CnD_importAll.jpg)

### When Importing Meshes

![](FBXImportOptions.png)

UE4 prompts you to define import options for FBX/OBJ files (pictured above).

### When Importing Textures

UE4 batch imports [__supported__](Engine/Content/Types/Textures/Importing "Click HERE to learn more about supported images.") image files for you.

If you see the following pop-up message:

![](TextureImportMessage.png)

UE4 just prevented you from importing an unsupported image file.

Also, if you see the following pop-up message:

![](nonpoweoftwowarning.png)

UE4 is telling you that odd-sized images aren't streamed or mipmapped.

## Importing from an External Program

(#Bookmark3)

Although we're using Photoshop in this example, you can follow along with any image editor of your choice.

### While Running Photoshop

Click **File** and **Save As**.

![](photoshop_export1.jpg)

### Inside the 'Save As' Dialog Box

Locating your UE4 Project Directory and Content folder, enter a filename (using a supported format), then click Save.

![](photoshop_export2.jpg)

### Browsing to your Content Folder

You'll see that your file has been added.

![](photoshop_export6.jpg)

If the Editor is open, the Processing outstanding content changes message will appear (pictured below).

![](photoshop_export4.jpg)

### Reviewing your Content Browser

Confirm that UE4 created a corresponding __*.uasset__ file.

![](photoshop_export5.jpg)

